create a helper function to remove undefined properties from an object
Certainly! Here's a helper function that removes undefined properties from an object:

```javascript
function removeUndefinedProperties(obj) {
  return Object.fromEntries(
    Object.entries(obj).filter(([_, value]) => value !== undefined)
  );
}
```

This function does the following:

1. It uses `Object.entries(obj)` to get an array of key-value pairs from the input object.

2. It then uses `filter()` to keep only the entries where the value is not undefined.

3. Finally, it uses `Object.fromEntries()` to convert the filtered array of entries back into an object.

You can use this function like this:

```javascript
const originalObject = {
  name: 'John',
  age: 30,
  city: undefined,
  country: 'USA',
  occupation: undefined
};

const cleanedObject = removeUndefinedProperties(originalObject);

console.log(cleanedObject);
// Output: { name: 'John', age: 30, country: 'USA' }
```

This helper function will work for plain objects. If you need to handle nested objects or arrays, you might want to create a more complex version that recursively processes nested structures.

Here's a version that handles nested objects and arrays:

```javascript
function removeUndefinedPropertiesDeep(obj) {
  if (Array.isArray(obj)) {
    return obj
      .map(item => removeUndefinedPropertiesDeep(item))
      .filter(item => item !== undefined);
  } else if (typeof obj === 'object' && obj !== null) {
    return Object.fromEntries(
      Object.entries(obj)
        .map(([key, value]) => [key, removeUndefinedPropertiesDeep(value)])
        .filter(([_, value]) => value !== undefined)
    );
  }
  return obj;
}
```

This version will recursively process nested objects and arrays, removing undefined values at all levels.
